              <span id="reviewTextContainer258670094" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14214885916380558439">So everyone knows about the Arthurian legends and that there isn&apos;t much historical evidence (if any) that Arthur existed. That said, this book strikes me as an accurate account of what it would have been like if such a warlord lived. The historical setting- Saxon raids, Irish conquerors, religious disputes, traces of Roman civilization, all that good stuff, is pretty accurate. Bernard Cornwell evidently did serious research into the way of life in 500ad, and it all gives a very authentic vibe. T</span>
  <span id="freeText14214885916380558439" style="display:none">So everyone knows about the Arthurian legends and that there isn't much historical evidence (if any) that Arthur existed. That said, this book strikes me as an accurate account of what it would have been like if such a warlord lived. The historical setting- Saxon raids, Irish conquerors, religious disputes, traces of Roman civilization, all that good stuff, is pretty accurate. Bernard Cornwell evidently did serious research into the way of life in 500ad, and it all gives a very authentic vibe. Things are portrayed as they were, with warriors wearing light armor to be more agile, Saxons wearing simple and crude armor (I absolutely praise the lack of impractical yet fancy demon-horned helmets), druids spiking their hair with dung, the lack of actual magic, and much more humanized characters.<br /><br />The narrator, Derfel Cadarn, is old and feeble, retelling Arthur's story to the current young queen Igraine. At this point (Book #1), some parts of the story are compromised due to his own beliefs (as pointed out by Igraine). Chiefly, his hatred towards Lancelot and the accusations of cowardice, and the praise to the Star of Powys and her beauty. We can't know if his descriptions are somewhat biased in some aspects, but that makes for an entertaining story. (On a lesser note, I also quite enjoyed Igraine's impatience to know what happens in the end, for I felt the same way. Derfel, however, kept the story linear, without jumping to spoilers, much to her discontent.)<br /><br />The main character, Arthur, is a very decent fellow. He empathizes with everyone (and by everyone I do mean everyone. Except Saxons.) and tries to be fair in judgement, tactful, respectful, brave, and honorable. Perhaps his major flaws are his love of Guinevere, his stubbornness, and his ambition. His ultimate goal is to unite Britain against foreign invasions and to secure his protegee the throne of Dumnonia, while leading that peace himself. Despite all this, he insults Powys by first betrothing the powisian princess and then abruptly marrying Guinevere out of mad, passionate, foolish love. (Lust?) And so the ultimate war begins, facing enemies on all sides- Franks fighting Armorica on the south (a kingdom Arthur had sworn to protect), Irish Blackshields and Kernow on the west, Siluria and Powys on the north, and Saxons on the East. War and madness all over the place, how much more real can this time period get? <br /><br />In the legends Merlin is a majestic, wise, kind even, Druid. In the book I thought he was more of a scumbag, using everyone for his own amusement, not caring for peoples' suffering. But yes, he was wise and feared by all, with the impatience at people's stupidity that I guess could only come with the knowledge and power he possessed. All in all, I liked him.<br /><br />As for a minor pet peeve, there is a ton of spit in this book. Everyone spits at everyone to insult them, to ward off evil, to release some anger, to prove a point, to curse... You get the idea.<br /><br />In conclusion, excellent, excellent book. Had me surprised at reading so much so suddenly without even realizing how much I had read. Recommended to people who want a realistic legend, who enjoy the Dark Ages, who like accurate historical settings, who believe chivalry shouldn't be dead, and who like ancient battles. I for one, am absolutely thrilled to read the next book in this series :)</span>
  <a data-text-id="14214885916380558439" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

