    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2851165327" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2851165327" />
    <a title="Sud666" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36890366-sud666"><img alt="Sud666" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1418437112p2/36890366.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2851165327?book_show_action=true">Jul 25, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sud666" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sud666" href="/user/show/36890366-sud666">Sud666</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/36890366-sud666?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/36890366-sud666?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2851165327" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11189034050007451198">Bernard Cornwell is one of my favorite writers of historical fiction. Thus, I was surprised to see him write a book about Arthur. I am certainly glad that I picked this up. It is a very strange book in that it technically belongs on my &quot;fantasy&quot; shelf, but the accuracy of the settings and weapons makes it a weak &quot;historical fiction&quot; as well. Mr. Cornwell admits as much, in the notes, when he points out that the monk Gildas&apos;s &quot;De Excidio et Conquestu Britanniae&quot; (written during the 540s) about th</span>
  <span id="freeText11189034050007451198" style="display:none">Bernard Cornwell is one of my favorite writers of historical fiction. Thus, I was surprised to see him write a book about Arthur. I am certainly glad that I picked this up. It is a very strange book in that it technically belongs on my "fantasy" shelf, but the accuracy of the settings and weapons makes it a weak "historical fiction" as well. Mr. Cornwell admits as much, in the notes, when he points out that the monk Gildas's "De Excidio et Conquestu Britanniae" (written during the 540s) about the Britons defeating a Saxon invasion never mentions Arthur. It is likely, as most historians believe, that he was a warlord though not a king.<br /><br />That is the premise for this story. Uther Pendragon is old, his bastard Arthur is banished to Britanny to learn from King Ban of Benoic and Merlin has been missing for several years. Modred, Uther's crippled heir, is born and Arthur returns to pledge himself as his protector. Meanwhile, a series of gaffes (this Arthur is noble but dense) causes the Britons to fight each other as the Saxons encroach on more land.<br /><br />It is in this setting that we see Arthur. The story is told through the eyes of Derfel, one of Arthur's warriors, and it has many of the characters from the better-known versions of the Arthurian legend. But there are subtle differences and I think, in order to make it more 'realistic", the changes work. Even the powers of Nimue or Merlin are no more, nor less, efficacious due to the sheer credulity of the people. Curses, wizards, druids, etc all had a deep-seated psychological appeal to people from this time and Cornwell shows their influence (though never ascribing them supernatural powers).<br /><br />I really enjoyed this "realistic" retelling of the Arthurian legend and anyone who enjoys either historical fiction or fantasy will appreciate this story. Apparently, this is only the first book so count me in for the rest of this series. Cornwell really does a great job with the legend and is able to retell it in a very realistic setting.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11189034050007451198" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


