        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1144378173" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7984804539426002670">7.5/10<br/><br/>It took a while for me to get into this, I was overwhelmed with the amount of names thrust at me from the off. From the start you&apos;ve learnt more characters names in the first few pages than most series will have in their entire run only for the majority of these to be killed off before you&apos;ve remembered who they are! Luckily, things steadied after a while and you had a core group and things became more focused and the story was able to really progress.<br/><br/>I guess the story of King Arthur and M</span>
  <span id="freeText7984804539426002670" style="display:none">7.5/10<br /><br />It took a while for me to get into this, I was overwhelmed with the amount of names thrust at me from the off. From the start you've learnt more characters names in the first few pages than most series will have in their entire run only for the majority of these to be killed off before you've remembered who they are! Luckily, things steadied after a while and you had a core group and things became more focused and the story was able to really progress.<br /><br />I guess the story of King Arthur and Merlin and his knights is quite well know but the more I read the more I realised I knew very little actually other than the sword and a few of the knights names which made for a more entertaining read as I had no idea who would do what or who would meet a grisly doom.<br /><br />Cornwell has a tendency to stick in massive descriptive passages which I personally struggled with at times. However, even with that said, I noticed at the latter stages of the book I found myself thinking about the book when I wasn't reading it and I needed to know what happened next which is always a good sign. At the finish I was grateful that there are two more books in the series and hoping now all the main characters have been introduced the next book will get straight into things without introducing a list of people as long as the telephone book.<br /><br />If you like this try: "Azincourt" by Bernard Cornwell </span>
  <a data-text-id="7984804539426002670" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

